First, we need to extract the key figures from the provided statements.

Step 1. Debt to Equity Ratio  
• From the balance sheet:  
 – Total Current Liabilities (which represent the liabilities in this case): 2,491,297.55  
 – Total Owner’s Equity: 11,598,563.11  
 • Debt to Equity Ratio = (Total Liabilities) / (Total Owner's Equity)  
  = 2,491,297.55 / 11,598,563.11 ≈ 0.2148  
  Rounded, this gives about 0.21

Step 2. Net Profit Margin  
• From the income statement:  
 – Net Profit: –1,401,436.89  
 – Total Revenue: 7,825,951.24  
 • Net Profit Margin = (Net Profit / Total Revenue) × 100%  
  = (–1,401,436.89 / 7,825,951.24) × 100% ≈ –17.91%

Step 3. Return on Assets (ROA)  
• From the balance sheet:  
 – Total Assets (End amount): 14,089,860.66  
 – Using Net Profit from income statement: –1,401,436.89  
 • ROA = (Net Profit / Total Assets) × 100%  
  = (–1,401,436.89 / 14,089,860.66) × 100% ≈ –9.95%

Step 4. Accounts Receivable Turnover Ratio  
For calculating Accounts Receivable Turnover, we use sales (revenue) divided by average accounts receivable.  
• From the balance sheet:  
 – Beginning Accounts Receivable: 0 (given the initial amount is 0)  
 – Ending Accounts Receivable: 1,988,616.02  
  Average Accounts Receivable = (0 + 1,988,616.02) / 2 = 994,308.01  
• From the income statement, Main Business Revenue = 7,825,951.24  
 • Accounts Receivable Turnover Ratio = Main Business Revenue / Average Accounts Receivable  
  = 7,825,951.24 / 994,308.01 ≈ 7.87

Thus, the final results are:

{
  "solution": {
    "Debt to Equity Ratio": "0.21",
    "Net Profit Margin": "-17.91%",
    "Return on Assets (ROA)": "-9.95%",
    "Accounts Receivable Turnover Ratio": "7.87"
  }
}
